# PROJECT INTENTION
# =============================================================================
#
# The primary goal of certbot-nginx is to provide a **more secure, auditable,
# and production-hardened** way to use Certbot with nginx.
#
# Key security improvements in 1.9.0:
#   • Drastically reduced root dependency after initial installation
#   • Introduction of a dedicated, least-privilege user "nginx-adm"
#   • All nginx configuration files and directories are owned by nginx-adm
#   • systemctl operations on nginx are allowed via a restricted sudoers file
#     (no password required, but only for nginx start/stop/reload/restart)
#   • nginx -t can be run directly as nginx-adm (no sudo is required)
#   • Better separation between "system installation" (still requires root)
#     and "day-to-day configuration & renewal" (can be done as nginx-adm)
#
# This design gives you the convenience of a one-command installer while
# following modern least-privilege principles and reducing the attack surface
# of running everything as root.
#
# =============================================================================
#
# PLATFORM SUPPORT (Updated April 2026)
# =============================================================================
#
# Primary / Fully Supported:
#   • Linux (Debian/Ubuntu, Alpine, RHEL/Fedora/Rocky/CentOS family)
#     - Uses native package managers (apt, apk, dnf/yum) or snap where appropriate
#   • macOS via Homebrew
#
# Limited / Best-Effort:
#   • openSUSE (zypper)
#
# Not Recommended / Unsupported:
#   • Git Bash / MSYS2 / native Windows
#     → Strong warning + recommendation to use WSL2 (Ubuntu)
#   • Other Unix-like systems without supported package managers
#
# Important Notes on Platform Differences:
#   • On most Linux distributions, the nginx package starts the service automatically after install.
#     This is expected — the script stops it immediately in stop_nginx_early().
#   • On macOS (Homebrew), nginx does not start automatically.
#   • /etc/letsencrypt paths and systemd commands are Linux-centric; macOS support is limited to installation only.
#   • The strict sequence (certs before full nginx config) is enforced on all supported platforms.
#
# The script remains focused on Linux as the primary target. Cross-platform support is defensive and best-effort.
#
# =============================================================================
#
# CRITICAL REQUIREMENTS - DO NOT DEVIATE (DEFENSIVE LOCK)
# =============================================================================
#
# 1. Email and Domain List Handling (MUST be done FIRST and INDEPENDENTLY)
#    • Before ANY Certbot installation, configuration, or certificate application:
#      - Collect email (for Let's Encrypt registration and notifications)
#      - Collect the PRIMARY / MAIN domain interactively from the user 
#        using get_main_domain() — this is the authoritative choice made by the user.
#      - Then allow the user to add additional domains (SANs) via confirmation.
#    • The main domain is chosen EXPLICITLY AND INTERACTIVELY by the user.
#      It is NOT determined by "the first item in the list".
#    • After confirmation (ask_and_confirm_domains), the script MUST re-arrange 
#      the final domain list so that the user-chosen main domain is placed FIRST.
#    • This main domain becomes the primary common name (CN) for the certificate.
#    • All other domains become Subject Alternative Names (SANs) in ONE single certificate.
#    • These values (email + final domain list with main domain at front) MUST be 
#      stored persistently in /etc/letsencrypt/ so they can be retrieved later.
#
# 2. Defensive Pre-Creation Rule (Good Practice - NEVER assume directories exist)
#    • ALWAYS attempt to create /etc/letsencrypt (and relevant subdirs) early
#    • Create empty or placeholder configuration files for email and domain list
#    • Whenever retrieving email or domain list later, re-create the folder
#      and placeholder files if they are missing.
#
# 3. nginx-adm Least-Privilege Model (NEW in 1.9.0)
#    • A dedicated normal user "nginx-adm" is created (if it does not exist).
#    • nginx-adm owns the entire ${NGINX_CONF_ROOT} directory tree.
#    • nginx-adm has its home directory at /etc/nginx-adm.
#    • ${NGINX_CONF_ROOT}/sites-enabled  → symlink to /etc/nginx-adm/sites-enabled
#    • ${NGINX_CONF_ROOT}/sites-available → symlink to /etc/nginx-adm/sites-available
#    • A restricted sudoers rule allows nginx-adm to run:
#        systemctl start/stop/reload/restart/status nginx   (NOPASSWD)
#    • Because nginx-adm owns ${NGINX_CONF_ROOT}, "nginx -t" can be executed directly
#      as nginx-adm — no sudo is required for configuration testing.
#    • This design allows future configuration/renewal operations to run as
#      nginx-adm instead of full root, significantly improving security.
#
# 4. Existing Nginx Configuration Backup Policy (NEW in 1.9.0)
#    • Before any modification to nginx configuration (especially during
#      initial setup or when regenerating configs), the script MUST create
#      a dated backup of any existing configuration files.
#    • Backup filename format: <original-name>.YYYYMMDD-N.bak
#      Example: default.conf.20260408-1.bak
#      (N starts at 1 and increments for multiple backups on the same day)
#    • Special rule for default.conf (or any default site config in sites-available):
#      After successful backup, the original default.conf MUST be removed
#      from sites-available. This ensures that on repeated installations there
#      will be only one backup file per day (no accumulation of default configs).
#    • All backups are created before any removal or symlink changes.
#    • This policy protects user custom configurations and provides safe rollback.
#
# 5. Strict Installation and Configuration Sequence 
#    for interactive mode
#    • Step 1: Install Certbot without plugin configuration
#    • Step 2: Install Nginx without configuration
#    • Step 3: Stop Nginx service early
#    • Step 4: Handle email and domains independently (user chooses main domain explicitly)
#    • Step 5: Ensure nginx is stopped → then run Certbot using the user-chosen main domain
#    • Step 6: ONLY AFTER certificates are successfully applied:
#              Setup the full Nginx configuration using the same main domain
#    • Step 7: Test config with nginx -t (as nginx-adm) then start nginx
#
#    for non-interactive mode
#    • Step 1: Install Certbot without plugin configuration
#    • Step 2: Install Nginx without configuration
#    • Step 3: Check if Nginx is running,
#              Immediately stop Nginx service (empty configuration has no use)
#
# Important Rule:
#    The main domain is decided by the USER interactively, not by list position.
#    After all confirmation steps, the script MUST force the user-chosen main domain 
#    to the front of the final domain list before saving and before using it for 
#    certificate and nginx configuration.
#
# Why this exact sequence?
#    - Prevents Nginx from ever running with empty or broken configuration
#    - Lets the internal certificate provider (Certbot) complete its work cleanly
#      before the external servant (Nginx) receives its final configuration
#    - Avoids common failures with --nginx plugin and partial setups
#    - Follows the internal (Certbot provides cert) → external (Nginx serves outside) model
#
# 6. Additional Hard Rules
#    • Do NOT start Nginx early or let it run with incomplete config
#    • Support --quiet and --json modes fully in all steps
#    • Never simplify, refactor, or "improve" the defensive repetition
#    • The first domain in the list is ALWAYS the primary common name for the certificate
#    • After initial setup, prefer running nginx-related commands as nginx-adm
#      whenever possible (least privilege principle)
#    • Backup policy (section 4) MUST be respected on every run that touches
#      nginx configuration files
#
