# =============================================================================
# NGINX CONFIGURATION STRUCTURE ACROSS PLATFORMS (April 2026)
# =============================================================================
#
# This project must support multiple OS families without forcing one layout.
# Below is the battlefield reality of default nginx installation structures:
#
# +---------------------+-------------------+---------------------+-------------------+--------------------------+
# | OS Family           | Config Root       | sites-available /   | Default Include     | Default Owner / Notes    |
# |                     |                   | sites-enabled       |                     |                          |
# +---------------------+-------------------+---------------------+-------------------+--------------------------+
# | Debian/Ubuntu       | /etc/nginx/       | Yes (default)       | sites-enabled/*     | root:root                |
# | RHEL/Rocky/CentOS   | /etc/nginx/       | No (conf.d only)    | conf.d/*.conf       | root:root                |
# | Alpine              | /etc/nginx/       | No (must create)    | conf.d/*.conf       | root:root (worker: www)  |
# | macOS Homebrew x86  | /usr/local/etc/nginx/ | No              | conf.d/* or servers/* | User who ran brew (often admin) |
# | macOS Homebrew arm  | /opt/homebrew/etc/nginx/ | No           | conf.d/* or servers/* | Same as above            |
# | macOS MacPorts      | /opt/local/etc/nginx/ | No              | conf.d/*            | root or macports         |
# +---------------------+-------------------+---------------------+-------------------+--------------------------+
#
# Key Observations:
#   • Only Debian-family creates sites-available + sites-enabled by default.
#   • Most other platforms use conf.d/*.conf convention.
#   • macOS paths are completely different from /etc/nginx.
#   • Ownership is almost always root:root on Linux, but not on macOS Homebrew.
#
# Our Strategy (User Preference):
#   1. Do NOT force one structure.
#   2. Prefer to make nginx.conf adopt sites-available / sites-enabled once (with backup).
#   3. Adapt detection and paths per platform.
#
# This comment block serves as the SINGLE SOURCE OF TRUTH for cross-platform nginx differences.
#
# !!! ANY FUTURE CHANGES TO CROSS-OS BEHAVIOR MUST UPDATE THIS TABLE !!!
# =============================================================================

# =============================================================================
# DOCUMENT ROOT (/var/www) STRUCTURE ACROSS PLATFORMS
# =============================================================================
#
# Default document root locations vary significantly by OS/package:
#
# +---------------------+--------------------------+-------------------------------+
# | OS Family           | Default Document Root    | Notes                         |
# +---------------------+--------------------------+-------------------------------+
# | Debian/Ubuntu       | /var/www/html            | Standard, www-data owner      |
# | RHEL/Rocky/CentOS   | /usr/share/nginx/html    | Different from Debian         |
# | Alpine              | /var/www/localhost/htdocs| Often customized              |
# | macOS Homebrew      | /usr/local/var/www       | or /opt/homebrew/var/www      |
# | macOS MacPorts      | /opt/local/share/nginx/html | Less common                |
# +---------------------+--------------------------+-------------------------------+
